## Initial Approach — Direct Tumor Segmentation

The initial methodology focused on directly detecting and isolating tumor regions from gross breast tissue images using color-based segmentation and thresholding techniques.

### Step 1 — Image Acquisition
Digital photographs of excised breast tissue samples were collected under normal clinical lighting conditions. The dataset included:
- Cancerous tissue
- Non-cancerous tissue
- Phyllodes tissue

The raw images contained background objects such as trays, cloth, and surgical surroundings.

---

### Step 2 — Background Removal

To isolate the tissue specimen from surrounding noise, GrabCut segmentation was applied.

Post-processing operations included:
- Morphological opening
- Morphological closing
- Noise removal
- Gap filling

This produced a cleaner tissue-only image for analysis.

---

### Step 3 — Tumor Detection using Color-Space Analysis

The tissue region was analyzed using:
- HSV color space
- LAB color space

The algorithm attempted to identify tumor regions using:
- High brightness regions
- Low saturation values
- Non-yellow tissue characteristics

The central region of the tissue specimen was prioritized to reduce edge artifacts and lighting inconsistencies.

---

### Step 4 — Tumor Segmentation

Detected tumor regions were converted into binary masks.

Small noisy regions were removed using connected-component filtering to retain only significant tissue regions.

---

### Step 5 — Feature Extraction

Features extracted from the segmented tumor regions included:

#### Shape Features
- Area
- Perimeter
- Circularity
- Aspect Ratio
- Solidity

#### Color Features
- Mean RGB values
- Mean HSV values

#### Texture Features
GLCM-based texture analysis:
- Contrast
- Dissimilarity
- Homogeneity
- Energy
- Correlation
- ASM

---

## Limitation of Initial Approach

The segmentation-based methodology proved unreliable because cancerous tissue did not exhibit consistent:
- color
- shape
- boundary structure

Benign tissues such as fat and fibrous regions often visually resembled malignant tissue, leading to frequent false detections.

Due to these inconsistencies, direct segmentation failed to robustly isolate tumor regions across different samples.

This limitation motivated the transition toward a patch-based feature engineering methodology.
